Due to Unhealthy Air Quality, KSD Will Operate Remotely & Will Distribute Meals

Kelso School District is committed to providing a safe and secure environment for our students and staff. Due to continuing unhealthy air quality in the local area, Kelso School District will operate in full remote mode for staff and students on Thursday, September 17. District buildings are closed to the public. No Internet Cafes, but meal distribution will be available at normally scheduled distribution sites.

We will continue to monitor air quality conditions during the day tomorrow, and provide an update as soon as possible about any schedule changes for Friday, September 18.

Due to hazardous air quality, Kelso schools will be completely remote with no meal distribution.

Kelso School District is committed to providing a safe and secure environment for our students and staff. Due to continuing hazardous air quality in Kelso, all in-person school services are canceled for Tuesday, September 15 and district buildings are closed to the public. This includes all onsite student learning, internet cafes, meal distribution, bus transportation, and other services at school and district offices.

Remote Learning will continue with students and staff working from home or off-site locations. Only essential staff will be required to report to district facilities.

We will continue to monitor air quality and weather conditions during the day tomorrow, and provide an update as soon as possible about any schedule changes for Wednesday, September 16.

post_text: On this last day of the school year we’d like to recognize the Class of 2020. As we send our seniors off to frontlines of their futures, we know they are entering a new world on many levels. Not only new in post-high school endeavors (college, trades, military, or work force), but also new in the changing way we do everything—from getting groceries and going to work to socializing and traveling. While this is, literally, a brave new world for them, we are confident in their abilities to rise to any occasion, overcome any obstacle, and represent Kelso “We Are” as they pursue their dreams. Congratulations, Class of 2020, on your new adventure!

post_text: Our parents and guardians deserve a standing ovation. In addition to dealing with stay at home orders, worrying about the health of their families, and toilet paper shortages, they’ve had to pick up monitoring their children’s remote education all while figuring out how to work from home, or dealing with the stress of being furloughed or laid off. We know these last few months haven’t been easy, and our hats are off to you. Thank you for adapting and being an example of how to survive and thrive during challenging times.

post_text:
The normally hardworking Human Resources, Payroll, and Business departments have been especially busy since the school closure in March. The usual processes of hiring, managing payroll and accounts payables are more challenging due to the need to keep up with fluctuating regulations, COVID-19 accounting, new and different kinds of leave, and ever-changing workplace regulations. The landscape is ever-evolving and these teams have exhibited incredible leadership.

Thanks for keeping all the wheels turning and doing it so well!
Scott Cantwell, Paula Edwards, Daelynn Ferrell, Kristine Hansen, Stephanie House, Darcy Hymes, Jill Kaufman, Loretta Lafave, Kristaa Mason, Courtney Peonio, Tim Peterson, Anna Roller, Amanda Sanders, and Scott Westlund

post_text:
When the school closure happened, our Teaching and Learning team found themselves having to reimagine education. Working with teachers and looking at everything through the lens of equity, they put a distance learning model in place and coordinated the tools to make it work. In addition to keeping their eye on engagement, this team has been creating professional development for our teachers around mastering the technical aspects of remote learning while maintaining the art of teaching.

Thanks for all your incredible work!
Lacey DeWeert, J’aime Graff, Gunnar Guttormsen, Marilyn Melville-Irvine, Lori Paul, Jan Rauth, Misa Reardon, Brenda Sargent, Kelsey Thompson, and Kim Yore

post_text:
As we finish this year after months of school closures, the next big question is what will school look like next year? To answer that, a Re-Opening Task Force of more than 20 stakeholders has been convened. Over several in-person meetings, the task force is developing recommendations and expectations for a fall model that fits Kelso kids, families, and staff based on data, feedback, and state agency requirements. Their plan will meet CDC, Health Department, Labor and Industry, and OPSI expectations. This group is reviewing OSPI models while considering input from all staff, families, and students. It’s a big job with lots of moving parts.

Thanks, Task Force, for taking on this important work:
Holly Budge, Lacey Deweert, Bob Gustin, Mike Haas, Angela Hansen, Laura Hiatt, Stefanie House, Don Iverson, Christine McDaniel, David McDaniel, Michele Nerland, Nicole Nickel, Roy Pennington, Tim Peterson, Gary Schimmel, Kelli Stewart, Mary Beth Tack, Stephanie Toms, Scott Westlund, and Kim Yore

For students, the transitions from elementary to middle school and from middle to high school can be difficult. Our counselors and administrators collaborate to ensure seamless transitions and have been working on the process and master schedule development since the school closure began. This work also includes: meeting with students individually by phone or Zoom, making welcome videos for students and parents, classroom Zoom meetings, and more.

We can’t thank you enough for your work to help all our students feel safe, excited, and welcome when they return to school: Kim Allais, Emily Allred, Rob Birdsell, Kylie Chapman, Cindy Cromwell, Kali Dalton, Zoe Dieter, Lavern Dollarhyde, Greg Gardner, Marla Green, Laura Hiatt, Angela Knowles, Rachel Leinweber, Sarah Marlow, Denise Miles-Foges, Makailo Mobbs, Cami Rothwell, Erin Schumacher, Justin Sitch, Rebecca Viscuso, and Chris Wiseman.

A big thank you to everyone on the Maintenance team for all you do!

post_text:
What Kali Dalton has done with senior scholarships has been pretty incredible. Since school closure, she has moved what was once a paper process to be fully digital. Kali has kept track of hundreds of submissions, created scripts for Scholarship Night, and is doing all she can to honor students who have already received scholarships from either their colleges or other outside organizations. She has partnered with Kelso School Foundation while working remotely for continued top-notch service.

Thanks so much, Kali, for all the time, effort, and considerable care you’ve put in for our seniors!

post_text:
To get online registration up and running in the district is no easy feat. There are over 135 fields to manage. It can be a daunting process and any extra clarifying wording or direction helps parents and guardians understand better and move more smoothly through the process of enrolling their student(s).

Before moving this process online, our team had to create advanced custom forms to gather data, automate emails alerting staff of new applications, and add security for processing. A webpage with links and detailed information needed to be put up, and staff needed to be trained on how to process and gather the data.

After weeks of tweaking and triple checking, thanks to Kelly Toftemark and Molly Guler, online registration is now available at bit.ly/ksd-enroll. Excellent work, Kelly and Molly!

In recent weeks, teams of staff from every school have been collecting, sorting, bagging and handing out their students' personal belongings. With social distancing and other COVID-19 protection measures, this once simple task has become quite a large undertaking. Approximately 176 of our teachers and staff spent 215 hours in the process and got personal belongings back to over 2,000 students.

Thanks, teams, for all your work on this! Even the Coweeman Cougar helped! #WeAre #InThisTogether #FrontlineHeroes

https://www.kelso.wednet.edu/o/ksd/page/belonging-collection-teams

These Hidden Heroes have not stopped serving the kids of Kelso since the closure announcement on March 13 and instantly moved from seat-based learning to distance learning for each and every Kelso student they serve. The courses they teach are closely tied to college transcripts and deadlines for testing that still remain in place even during college and K-12 closures. Total enrollment for these classes is 736, with 199 unduplicated students.

Our nutrition services team went into action immediately after the school closure was announced. Within days they were prepping grab and go breakfasts and lunches for our students. They’re in our cafeterias receiving food shipments, packaging grab and go bags, and distributing them at our schools.

Since March 19th, this group of heroes have prepared nearly 40,000 meals. Thanks so much, Nutrition Services, for all you do for our families!

post_text:
Since the school closure, this team has continued their support and services to our families with a combination of worksheets, website & online activity recommendations, family consultations, providing social stories or visual schedules, and/or teletherapy - all through virtual platforms, phone calls, and email.

These dedicated and thoughtful practitioners are making good faith efforts to support our students with disabilities by maintaining a focus on supportive relationships with students and families, beyond considerations for instructional content.

Since March 16th, our Kelso Special Education staff have managed to balance compassion with compliance – completing 110 IEP's, 23 evaluations/reevaluations, and 26 reevaluation waivers.

A special shout-out to Director Holly Budge, Julie Chrest, and Becky Kent for working behind the scenes to support the families, staff, and Kelso students.
https://www.kelso.wednet.edu/o/ksd/page/special-education-team--6
text:
Since the school closure, this team has continued their support and services to our families with a combination of worksheets, website & online activity recommendations, family consultations, providing social stories or visual schedules, and/or teletherapy - all through virtual platforms, phone calls, and email.

These dedicated and thoughtful practitioners are making good faith efforts to support our students with disabilities by maintaining a focus on supportive relationships with students and families, beyond considerations for instructional content.

Since March 16th, our Kelso Special Education staff have managed to balance compassion with compliance – completing 110 IEP's, 23 evaluations/reevaluations, and 26 reevaluation waivers.

A special shout-out to Director Holly Budge, Julie Chrest, and Becky Kent for working behind the scenes to support the families, staff, and Kelso students.
https://www.kelso.wednet.edu/o/ksd/page/special-education-team--6

In addition to those on the frontlines, KSD has many Hidden Heroes: people behind the scenes, with tasks and jobs just as vital. Join us in celebrating all these heroic people and teams, working to keep things going during the extended COVID closure.

Our district instructional coaches quickly created high-quality learning packets for K-5 students focused around our 3 strategic areas: English language arts (Ready GEN), Math (IReady), and Social Emotional Learning (Second Steps). Then, a team assembled close to 2,500 packets to support our young learners.

(Many thanks to our instructional coaches: Jan Rauth, Marilyn Melville-Irvine, Gunnar Guttormsen, Jake Alabiso, Bob Johanson, Misa Reardon and Director Kim Yore; and the assembly team: Lori Paul, Holly Budge, Don Iverson, Olivia Stephenson, Amy Delagrange, Julie Chrest, Julie Owens-Birch, Ray Cattin, Lacey Deweert, and Mark Connolly.)

Our custodians also gathered over 2,500 masks to donate to our Cowlitz County Incident Management Team (IMT). The IMT is coordinating the local response to the COVID-19 pandemic.

post_text: Feeling stressed or anxious? Here are some tips from the CDC, put into a colorful graphic. Take care of yourselves. <3 #KelsoCares #InThisTogether
shared_text:
Blessing Manifesting
March 12 at 12:45 PM ·

I think we can all agree that the coronavirus (COVID-19) is pretty heavily on everyone's mind. I got a message from someone under quarantine in Italy who asked if I could make a graphic about how to handle the anxiety and fear of this whole thing and honestly that's hard to do because I'm anxious and afraid too.

The CDC and Mentalhealth.org.uk put out some great tips so I shared them in a blog post (link in comments) and made this image.

It's okay to be scared/anxious/depressed over what's happening around the world. It's okay to talk about it. It's okay to ramp up the self-care. It's okay to seek extra mental health support. Take care of yourself out there.

post_text: In case you haven't seen this, we thought you should be aware. We have sent information to families in the area and informed students.
shared_text:
Kelso Police Department
September 5, 2019 at 7:55 PM ·

The Kelso Police Department earlier this morning investigated a shooting in the 1000 block of South 8th Avenue. The suspect was apprehended without incident in the 1300 block of South 8th. The gun, believed to be a handgun, used in this incident has not been recovered and is believed it could possibly be in the area. Residents and children walking in the area should be aware of this and call 911 immediately if they find a firearm. Please do not touch the firearm.

post_text: Way to go, Megan!
shared_text:
Lower Columbia College Running Start added a new photo to the album: 2019 Graduates.
March 21, 2019 at 5:48 PM ·

We're so proud of our Running Start students! Megan is a Running Start Senior who will graduate from Lower Columbia College with her AA-DTA in Spring 2019. She will transfer to Central Washington University where she will major in Construction Management. She's been on LCC's President’s List multiple times and is a member of Phi Theta Kappa and the National Honor Society. Additionally she is part of the Kelso High school band and is a leader for the percussion section. Megan said, “[I would like to thank] my parents for encouraging me and motivating me to do my best. My band director, Daniel Hartley, for teaching me music and giving me life lessons along the way.” Good work, Megan. You’ll go far!

Feel free to tag and share!

Kelso High School is participating in a great program called TEALS that pairs computer science volunteers with teachers who are introducing computer science classes at the high school. We are looking for volunteers for next year’s classes.

If you have a degree in computer science or experience in computer programming and can dedicate about 1-2 hours a week (you’ll be done by 9:00 AM) please contact brenda.sargent@kelsosd.org for more information.

We’d love to have you join our team as we prepare Kelso students for 21st century jobs. For more information, check out https://www.tealsk12.org/volunteers/.

Kelso High School set a Pacific NW record of 245 Healthy Youth Heart Screenings in one day—outpacing all schools in Oregon and Washington!

As part of our district's “Whole Child Initiative”, we teamed up with Providence Health to offer a free Play Smart, Youth Heart Screening Clinic last week at KHS. Most kids have healthy hearts, but some have hidden heart defects that potentially can put them at risk, especially during physical activities.

We’d love to hear your thoughts on a proposed change in construction plans for replacing our aging elementary schools. Join us tonight or January 9th at KHS.

Rough renderings of proposed plans for the larger school at Lexington will be available for viewing, as will renderings for the new Wallace Elementary. A construction budget station will also be available at both open houses.
